==English==

===Alternative forms===
* [[synœcism]]

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|grc}} {{term|συνοικισμός|sc=polytonic}}, from {{term|συνοικίζειν||to make live with, to unite under one city|sc=polytonic}}, from {{term|σύν||[[syn-]]|sc=polytonic}} + {{term|οἰκίζειν||to colonise|sc=polytonic}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/sɪˈniːsɪzəm/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{context|Ancient Greece}} The [[unification]] of towns, tribes etc. under one [[capital city]] or [[polis]].

===Example sentences===
*"They always remained separate states and were never '''synoikised'''."<ref>''English History Review'', 1886, I, pg 636.</ref>
*"Legends...current before the villages were '''synoecised''' into Athens."<ref>''Myth, Ritual & Religion'', Andrew Lang, 1887, I, pg 266.</ref>
*"When the town was first formed...by the '''synœcism''' of the neighboring villages."<ref>''Encyclopædia Britannica'', Vol. XXX. 529/2.</ref>

